A property contributes to definition, yes — but no single property fully defines a complex thing.

What we usually call an “identity” is closer to:

a persistent pattern across many interacting properties over time.

So:

* one property gives a slice
* a collection gives a profile
* dynamics across time give continuity

Even then, the model is incomplete.

A person is not reducible to:

* height
* income
* IQ
* personality score
* political affiliation
* diagnosis
* social status

But all of those can still describe aspects of the system.

This tension shows up everywhere:

* science tries to measure
* life exceeds measurement
* measurement improves prediction
* over-reduction loses meaning

And yes — humans are constantly orienting toward standards.

Biologically, socially, psychologically:
we calibrate ourselves against perceived attractors.

Examples:

* beauty standards
* moral standards
* status hierarchies
* competency ideals
* archetypes
* professional benchmarks
* cultural myths
* role models

A “standard” is often:

a compressed representation of desirable traits within a system.

The problem is that standards can be:

* healthy
* adaptive
* pathological
* manipulated
* impossible
* outdated
* optimized for the wrong environment

Social media intensified this massively because it exposed people to:

* global comparison
* algorithmically amplified ideals
* curated lives
* statistical outliers presented as normal

So humans began calibrating themselves against increasingly unrealistic aggregates.

And because humans are mimetic creatures, desire itself becomes contagious.

We often don’t just want things.
We want what other people appear to value.

That creates runaway loops:

* attention shaping standards
* standards shaping behavior
* behavior reinforcing algorithms
* algorithms amplifying extremes

But deeper than social comparison, there’s another layer:
people often seek standards because standards provide:

* orientation
* meaning
* aspiration
* coordination
* identity stabilization

Without standards, systems drift into incoherence.
With overly rigid standards, systems suffocate.

Healthy standards tend to function more like:

* guiding stars
    than
* cages.

Something to orient by, not perfectly become.

And importantly:
different environments reward different property constellations.

The “ideal” trait set for:

* a monk
* a warrior
* a scientist
* a parent
* an artist
* a startup founder
* a farmer

are not identical.

So part of maturity is learning:

* which standards are externally imposed,
* which are locally adaptive,
* and which actually align with the life you want to build.